<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-transverse-tangents-to-two-circles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Transverse Tangents to Two Circles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Construct direct and transverse common tangents to two circles
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To guide learners to discover that exactly two transverse common tangents exist for two separate circles, that these tangents cross between the circles, and that both tangents meet at a single point between the two centres.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Prepare a sheet with two pre-drawn circles of clearly different sizes for learners who struggle to draw their own. Circulate and prompt: <q>Does your line cross between the two circles? Are the circles on opposite sides of the line? Where do your two lines meet when you extend them?</q>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Discovering Transverse Common Tangents</title>
                <p>
                    In this activity you will draw pairs of circles and look for straight lines that are tangent to both circles but cross between them.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using a compass (or by tracing two circular objects of different sizes), draw two circles that do not overlap and are not inside each other. Label the centres <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Try to draw a straight line that touches circle <m>A</m> at exactly one point and circle <m>B</m> at exactly one point, with the two circles on <em>opposite sides</em> of the line. How many such lines can you draw? Record your answer in the table below.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Extend both lines you found until they meet. Where does the meeting point lie in relation to the line <m>AB</m>?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    The meeting point should lie on the segment <m>AB</m>, between the two circles. Learners may notice that it divides <m>AB</m> in a fixed ratio related to the two radii.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Repeat parts (a)–(c) with two more pairs of circles, choosing different sizes and distances each time.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write a conjecture: how many transverse common tangents do two separate, non-overlapping circles always have?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    Exactly two. Learners should state that two separate circles always have exactly two transverse common tangents, and that both tangents pass through the same point on segment <m>AB</m>, between the two circles.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <title>Transverse common tangent observations</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Pair</cell>
                            <cell>Radius of circle <m>A</m></cell>
                            <cell>Radius of circle <m>B</m></cell>
                            <cell>Number of transverse tangents found</cell>
                            <cell>Do the tangents meet between the circles?</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>1</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>2</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>3</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the concept of a transverse common tangent and teach the compass-and-straightedge construction step by step.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Confirm that everyone found exactly two tangents crossing between the circles. Ask a learner to describe where the two lines met — establish together that this point always lies on segment <m>AB</m>, between the two circles.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Work through the construction steps in the Key Ideas box below. Demonstrate each step on the board before asking learners to follow along at their desks. Point out clearly that the auxiliary circle here has radius <m>R + r</m>, not <m>R - r</m> as in the direct tangent construction.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Emphasise that the auxiliary circle (radius <m>R + r</m>) and the semicircle on <m>AB</m> are construction tools only — they do not appear in the final diagram.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A <term>transverse common tangent</term> to two circles is a straight line that is tangent to both circles and leaves the two circles on <em>opposite sides</em> of the line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Two circles that do not overlap and are not inside each other have exactly <em>two</em> transverse common tangents, provided the circles do not touch.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Both transverse common tangents pass through a single point <m>O'</m> on the line through the centres, <em>between</em> the two circles. The point <m>O'</m> divides segment <m>AB</m> in the ratio <m>AO' : O'B = r : R</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The length <m>L</m> of a transverse common tangent is given by
                        <md>
                            <mrow>L = \sqrt{d^2 - (R + r)^2}</mrow>
                        </md>
                        where <m>d = AB</m> is the distance between the centres. This formula requires <m>d \gt R + r</m>; if <m>d \leq R + r</m> the circles overlap and no transverse common tangent exists.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Construction of a Transverse Common Tangent</title>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Draw the two circles with centres <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>) and <m>B</m> (radius <m>R</m>), and draw a line through the centres (that continues beyond them).
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-1">
                <caption>
                    Setting up the diagram.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Draw an <term>auxiliary circle</term> centred at <m>B</m> with radius <m>R + r</m>. (This is the key difference from the direct tangent construction, where the auxiliary circle had radius <m>R - r</m>.)
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-2">
                <caption>
                    Drawing the auxiliary circle (light red) centred at <m>B</m> with radius <m>R + r</m>. We can do so by picking any point on the circumference of circle <m>B</m>, drawing a circle through it with radius <m>r</m>, and marking the intersection of the ray from <m>B</m> to this point with that (light blue) circle.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center B angle 60 radius \R] \tkzGetPoint{W}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLL(T',h)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](O,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T}{T}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,W)(W, \r) \tkzGetPoints{W1}{W2}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](W,\r) \tkzGetPoint{d}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thin](W,d)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B, W, W2)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0 and 0.6](B,W)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find the midpoint <m>I</m> of segment <m>AB</m>.
                </p>
                 <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-3">
                <caption>
                    Point I is the midpoint of AB.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLL(T',h)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](O,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T}{T}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzInterCC(A,B)(B,A) \tkzGetPoints{i}{j}
                            \tkzCompass(A,i)\tkzCompass(A,j)
                            \tkzCompass(B,i)\tkzCompass(B,j)
                            \tkzDrawLine[very thin, add=0.1 and 0.1](i,j)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,I)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Draw the <term>connecting circle</term> centred at <m>I</m> with radius <m>IA</m>. Use a dashed line.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-4">
                <caption>
                    Creating the connecting circle (dashed orange) centred at the midpoint <m>I</m> of <m>AB</m>.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLL(T',h)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](O,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T}{T}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, thick, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T',I)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Label <m>Q</m> as one of the intersection points of the connecting circle and the auxiliary circle.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-5">
                <caption>
                    <m>Q</m> is the intersection of the dashed orange (connecting) and light red (auxiliary) circles.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLL(T',h)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](O,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T}{T}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, thick, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,Q, I)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Draw the ray from <m>Q</m> through <m>B</m> and label the intersection with circle <m>B</m> as <m>T_1'</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-7">
                <caption>
                    Ray <m>QB</m> meets the original red circle at <m>T_1'</m>.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLL(T',h)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](O,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T}{T}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, thick, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T',Q, I)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines(B,Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right](T'){$T_1$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    At <m>T_1'</m>, construct the tangent to circle <m>B</m> (draw a line through <m>T_1'</m> perpendicular to the radius <m>BT_1'</m>). Extend this tangent until it meets the circle <m>A</m>, where it is tangent. Label the tangent point on circle <m>A</m> as <m>T_1</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-8">
                <caption>
                    First transverse tangent drawn.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLL(T',h)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](O,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T}{T}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, thick, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T',T,Q, I)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines(T',T B,Q A,T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right](T){$T_1$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left](T'){$T'_1$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Label <m>Q'</m> as the other intersection point from Step 5. Repeat Steps 6 and 7 using <m>Q'</m> in place of <m>Q</m> to obtain the second direct common tangent, <m>T_2T'_2</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-9">
                <caption>
                    First transverse tangent drawn.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLL(T',h)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](O,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T}{T}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, thick, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T',T,Q, I)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines(T',T B,Q A,T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right](T){$T_1$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left](T'){$T'_1$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Label <m>Q'</m> as the other intersection point from Step 5. Repeat Steps 6–9 using <m>Q'</m> in place of <m>Q</m> to obtain the second transverse common tangent.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangents-construction-10">
                <caption>
                    First transverse tangent drawn.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A,5/1/B,2/3/K}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rt) \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{X'}{T'}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q')(B,\R) \tkzGetPoints{T2'}{X2'}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](h,T')(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{e}{T}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T2'](B) \tkzGetPoint{h2}
                            \tkzInterLC[R](T2',h2)(A,\r) \tkzGetPoints{T2}{T2}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, thick, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T',T,Q,Q',I,T2',T2)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.6](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines(T',T B,Q A,T T2',T2 B,Q' A,T2)
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below](Q')
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](T){$T_1$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left, xshift=-5pt](T'){$T'_1$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](T2){$T_2$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[left, xshift=-5pt](T2'){$T'_2$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                </figure>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </paragraphs>


    <p>
        It is helpful to compare the transverse tangent construction directly with the direct tangent construction from the previous section. The two constructions are almost identical in procedure; the key differences are summarised below.
    </p>

    <tabular halign="left" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
            <cell>Feature</cell>
            <cell>Direct common tangents</cell>
            <cell>Transverse common tangents</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>Circles' position relative to the tangent line</cell>
            <cell>Same side</cell>
            <cell>Opposite sides</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>Radius of auxiliary circle at <m>B</m></cell>
            <cell><m>R - r</m></cell>
            <cell><m>R + r</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>Direction to tangent point <m>T'</m> from <m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell>Ray <m>B \to Q</m> extended to circle <m>B</m></cell>
            <cell>Ray <m>Q \to B</m>, extended <em>past</em> <m>B</m> to circle <m>B</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>Where the two tangents meet</cell>
            <cell>Outside the circles, beyond <m>A</m></cell>
            <cell>Between the two circles, on segment <m>AB</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>Length formula</cell>
            <cell><m>\sqrt{d^2 - (R-r)^2}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\sqrt{d^2 - (R+r)^2}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>Existence condition</cell>
            <cell><m>d \gt R - r</m> (one circle must not be completely inside the other)</cell>
            <cell><m>d \gt R + r</m> (circles must not touch or overlap)</cell>
        </row>
    </tabular>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example xml:id="ex-transverse-tangent-construction">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Two circles have centres <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> with radii 2 cm and 5 cm respectively. The distance <m>AB = 9</m> cm. Using a compass and ruler, construct the transverse common tangents to the two circles.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-2-5-9-construction">
                <caption>
                    Two circles with centres <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, with <m>AB = 9</m> cm.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{5}%
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){A}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-30:9){B}
                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefShiftPoint[b](-2*\R, 0){b1}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B)
                            \tkzDrawSegment(A,B)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[blue](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[red](B,b1)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, fill=white, opacity=0.5](A,B){$9$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped](A,a){$2$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped](B,b1){$5$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Follow the construction steps from the Key Ideas box above.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw circle <m>A</m> with radius 2 cm and circle <m>B</m> with radius 5 cm, with <m>AB = 9</m> cm.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Set your compass to <m>R + r = 5 + 2 = 7</m> cm. Draw an auxiliary circle centred at <m>B</m> with radius 7 cm (dashed).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Bisect <m>AB</m> to find the midpoint <m>I</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Set your compass to <m>IA = IB = 4.5</m> cm. Draw the semicircle on diameter <m>AB</m> (dashed).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Mark the two intersection points <m>Q</m> and <m>Q'</m> of the semicircle and the auxiliary circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw the ray from <m>Q</m> through <m>B</m>, continuing past <m>B</m> to meet circle <m>B</m> at <m>T_1'</m>. Construct the tangent to circle <m>B</m> at <m>T_1'</m>; extend it to meet segment <m>AB</m> at <m>O'</m>. Draw line <m>O'T_1'</m> extended to meet circle <m>A</m> at <m>T_1</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Repeat using <m>Q'</m> to find the second tangent <m>T_2 T_2'</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-2-5-9-soln">
                <caption>
                    The completed construction, showing both transverse common tangents meeting at <m>O'</m> between the circles.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <!-- Image adapted from https://altermundus.fr/files/tkz-euclide/tkz-euclide.pdf p. 232 -->
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{5}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){A}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-30:9){B}
                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T1p}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h1}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h1--T1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T1}
                            \tkzInterLC[near](Q',B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T2p}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T2p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h2}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h2--T2p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T2}
                            \tkzInterLL(T1,T1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Op}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawCircles[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircles[red](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, thick, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.2 and 0.2](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawLines[add=0.2 and 0.2](T1,T1p T2,T2p)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(Q,B Q',B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,I,Q,Q',T1,T1p,T2,T2p,Op)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzLabelPoints(A,B,I)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below](Q')
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T1){$T_1$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](T1p){$T'_1$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](T2){$T_2$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](T2p){$T'_2$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](Op){$O'$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-transverse-tangent-length">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Two circles have their centres 17 cm apart. Their radii are 3 cm and 5 cm. Calculate the length of a transverse common tangent.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let the centres be <m>A</m> (radius <m>r = 3</m> cm) and <m>B</m> (radius <m>R = 5</m> cm), with <m>AB = d = 17</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                Draw a line through <m>A</m> parallel to the tangent <m>TT'</m>, meeting the extension of <m>BT'</m> beyond <m>T'</m> at a point <m>M</m>. This creates a right triangle with:
                <ul>
                    <li><p>hypotenuse <m>AB = 17</m> cm,</p></li>
                    <li><p>one leg <m>BM = R + r = 5 + 3 = 8</m> cm,</p></li>
                    <li><p>other leg <m>AM = TT'</m> (the length we want).</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-tangent-formula">
                <caption>
                    The right triangle <m>ABM</m> used to derive the transverse tangent length formula.
                    Here <m>r = 3</m> cm, <m>R = 5</m> cm, <m>d = 17</m> cm, and <m>BM = R + r = 8</m> cm.
                </caption>
                <image width="90%">
                    <shortdescription>
                        Circles at A and B on opposite sides of a transverse common tangent TT-prime.
                        A dashed line from A parallel to the tangent meets the extension of radius
                        BT-prime beyond T-prime at M, forming right triangle ABM with the right
                        angle at M.
                    </shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.45]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{3}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{5}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 17/0/B}
                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{Tp}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=Tp](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h--Tp](A) \tkzGetPoint{T}
                            \tkzDefLine[parallel=through A](T,Tp) \tkzGetPoint{aP}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,aP)(B,Tp) \tkzGetPoint{M}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed, gray](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[thin](A,T B,M)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[very thick](T,Tp)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](A,M)
                            %% --- MARK ---
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.4](A,M,B)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](Tp,T,A)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](T,Tp,B)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T,Tp,M)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T){$T$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](Tp){$T'$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](M){$M$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below,font=\small](A,B){$d = 17$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left,font=\small](A,T){$r{=}3$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above,sloped,font=\small](T,Tp){$L = 15$ cm}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](B,Tp){$R{=}5$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](Tp,M){$r{=}3$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <p>
                By Pythagoras:
                <md>
                    <mrow> TT'^2 \amp= AB^2 - (R + r)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>       \amp= 17^2 - 8^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>       \amp= 289 - 64 </mrow>
                    <mrow>       \amp= 225 </mrow>
                    <mrow> TT'  \amp= 15 \text{ cm} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The length of the transverse common tangent is <m>15</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <theorem xml:id="length-of-transverse-tangent">
        <title>Length of the Transverse Tangent</title>
        <p>
            Generalising the previous example, if we have two circles with radii <m>r</m> and <m>R</m> and the distance between their centres is <m>d</m>, then the length of the transverse common tangent <m>L</m> is given by:
            <md>
                <mrow> L \amp= \sqrt{d^2 - (R + r)^2} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            You'll prove this in <xref ref="ex-transverse-tangent-length-proof"/>.
        </p>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex-transverse-tangent-find-d">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Two circles have radii 2 cm and 6 cm. The length of their transverse common tangent is 15 cm. Find the distance between the centres.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let the distance between the centres be <m>d</m> cm. Using the transverse common tangent length formula:
                <md>
                    <mrow> L^2 \amp= d^2 - (R + r)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> 15^2 \amp= d^2 - (6 + 2)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>  225 \amp= d^2 - 64 </mrow>
                    <mrow> d^2 \amp= 289 </mrow>
                    <mrow>   d \amp= 17 \text{ cm} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The distance between the centres is <m>17</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In each part, two circles are given. Using a compass and ruler, construct both transverse common tangents. Mark the point <m>O'</m> where they meet in each case.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Circle <m>A</m> with radius 1 cm, circle <m>B</m> with radius 3 cm, centres 6 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Circle <m>A</m> with radius 2 cm, circle <m>B</m> with radius 4 cm, centres 9 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Circle <m>A</m> with radius 1.5 cm, circle <m>B</m> with radius 3.5 cm, centres 8 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The diagrams show the two completed transverse common tangents for each configuration. Both tangent lines, when extended, meet at the point <m>O'</m> on segment <m>AB</m> between the two circles.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-exer1a-transverse">
                                <caption>Part (a): <m>r = 1</m>, <m>R = 3</m>, <m>d = 6</m> cm.</caption>
                                <image>
                                    <shortdescription>
                                        Two circles at A and B with two transverse common tangents meeting at O-prime between the circles.
                                    </shortdescription>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                                        %% --- SET ---
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{3}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B}
                                        %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T1p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h1--T1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T1}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q',B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T2p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T2p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h2--T2p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T2}
                                        \tkzInterLL(T1,T1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Op}
                                        %% --- DRAW ---
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,a)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,b)
                                        \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.3](T1,T1p T2,T2p)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,Op)
                                        %% --- LABEL ---
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$B$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](Op){$O'$}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-exer1b-transverse">
                                <caption>Part (b): <m>r = 2</m>, <m>R = 4</m>, <m>d = 9</m> cm.</caption>
                                <image>
                                    <shortdescription>
                                        Two circles at A and B with two transverse common tangents meeting at O-prime between the circles.
                                    </shortdescription>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.45]
                                        %% --- SET ---
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{2}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{4}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 9/0/B}
                                        %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T1p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h1--T1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T1}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q',B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T2p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T2p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h2--T2p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T2}
                                        \tkzInterLL(T1,T1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Op}
                                        %% --- DRAW ---
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,a)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,b)
                                        \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.3](T1,T1p T2,T2p)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,Op)
                                        %% --- LABEL ---
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$B$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](Op){$O'$}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-exer1c-transverse">
                                <caption>Part (c): <m>r = 1.5</m>, <m>R = 3.5</m>, <m>d = 8</m> cm.</caption>
                                <image>
                                    <shortdescription>
                                        Two circles at A and B with two transverse common tangents meeting at O-prime between the circles.
                                    </shortdescription>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                                        %% --- SET ---
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1.5}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{3.5}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 8/0/B}
                                        %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T1p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h1--T1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T1}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q',B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T2p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T2p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h2--T2p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T2}
                                        \tkzInterLL(T1,T1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Op}
                                        %% --- DRAW ---
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,a)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,b)
                                        \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.3](T1,T1p T2,T2p)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,Op)
                                        %% --- LABEL ---
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$B$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](Op){$O'$}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two circles of <em>equal</em> radius 2 cm have centres <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> that are 8 cm apart.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Construct both transverse common tangents to the two circles. What radius should your auxiliary circle have?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Where does the meeting point <m>O'</m> of the two tangents lie? Explain why this happens for circles of equal radius.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The auxiliary circle has radius <m>R + r = 2 + 2 = 4</m> cm. The rest of the construction is unchanged.
                            </p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-exer-equal-transverse">
                                <caption>Equal circles: <m>r = R = 2</m> cm, <m>d = 8</m> cm. The tangents meet at the midpoint of <m>AB</m>.</caption>
                                <image>
                                    <shortdescription>
                                        Two equal circles at A and B with two transverse common tangents crossing at the midpoint of segment AB.
                                    </shortdescription>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                                        %% --- SET ---
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{2}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{2}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 8/0/B}
                                        %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T1p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h1--T1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T1}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q',B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T2p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T2p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h2--T2p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T2}
                                        \tkzInterLL(T1,T1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Op}
                                        %% --- DRAW ---
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,a)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,b)
                                        \tkzDrawSegment[dashed,gray](A,B)
                                        \tkzDrawLines[add=0.3 and 0.3](T1,T1p T2,T2p)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,Op)
                                        %% --- LABEL ---
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$B$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below right](Op){$O'$}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>O'</m> is the exact midpoint of <m>AB</m>. The point <m>O'</m> divides <m>AB</m> in the ratio <m>AO' : O'B = r : R</m>; when <m>r = R</m> this ratio is <m>1 : 1</m>, so <m>O'</m> is the midpoint.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Circle <m>A</m> has radius 1 cm and circle <m>B</m> has radius 3 cm. Their centres are 8 cm apart.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                On a single diagram, construct both <em>direct</em> common tangents (auxiliary circle of radius <m>R - r</m>) and both <em>transverse</em> common tangents (auxiliary circle of radius <m>R + r</m>).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Mark the point <m>O</m> where the direct tangents meet and the point <m>O'</m> where the transverse tangents meet.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How many common tangents do two separate, non-overlapping circles have in total?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Carry out the direct tangent construction with auxiliary radius <m>R - r = 2</m> cm, then the transverse construction on the same diagram with auxiliary radius <m>R + r = 4</m> cm.
                            </p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-exer-both-tangent-types">
                                <caption>All four common tangents: direct tangents meet at <m>O</m>, transverse tangents meet at <m>O'</m>.</caption>
                                <image width="90%">
                                    <shortdescription>
                                        Two circles at A and B with four common tangent lines: two direct tangents meeting at O on line AB beyond the smaller circle, and two transverse tangents meeting at O-prime between the circles.
                                    </shortdescription>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                                        %% --- SET ---
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{1}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{3}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\rdiff}{\R-\r}%
                                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\rsum}{\R+\r}%
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 8/0/B}
                                        %% --- CALCULATE ---
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rdiff) \tkzGetPoint{cd}
                                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rsum) \tkzGetPoint{cs}
                                        \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                                        % Direct tangents
                                        \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,cd) \tkzGetPoints{P}{P'}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](P,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{D1p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=D1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{g1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto g1--D1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{D1}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](P',B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{D2p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=D2p](B) \tkzGetPoint{g2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto g2--D2p](A) \tkzGetPoint{D2}
                                        \tkzInterLL(D1,D1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                        % Transverse tangents
                                        \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,cs) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T1p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h1}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h1--T1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T1}
                                        \tkzInterLC[near](Q',B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T2p}
                                        \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T2p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h2}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h2--T2p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T2}
                                        \tkzInterLL(T1,T1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Op}
                                        %% --- DRAW ---
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,a)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,b)
                                        \tkzDrawSegment[dashed,gray](O,B)
                                        \tkzDrawLines[add=0 and 0.2](O,D1p O,D2p)
                                        \tkzDrawLines[add=0.2 and 0.2](T1,T1p T2,T2p)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,O,Op)
                                        %% --- LABEL ---
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](B){$B$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](O){$O$}
                                        \tkzLabelPoint[below right](Op){$O'$}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>O</m> lies on line <m>AB</m> extended, beyond the smaller circle <m>A</m>; <m>O'</m> lies on segment <m>AB</m>, between the two circles, as shown in the figure.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Four: two direct common tangents and two transverse common tangents.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-transverse-construction-why">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    This exercise explains <em>why</em> the construction in the Key Ideas box always produces a transverse common tangent. Recall the construction for two circles with centres <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>) and <m>B</m> (radius <m>R</m>):
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p>the <term>connecting circle</term> has <m>AB</m> as a diameter (centre <m>I</m>, the midpoint of <m>AB</m>);</p></li>
                    <li><p>the <term>auxiliary circle</term> has centre <m>B</m> and radius <m>R + r</m>;</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>Q</m> is a point where these two circles meet;</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>T_1'</m> is the point where line <m>QB</m> meets circle <m>B</m> between <m>Q</m> and <m>B</m>, and the tangent line is drawn through <m>T_1'</m> at right angles to the radius <m>BT_1'</m>.</p></li>
                </ul>
                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-why">
                    <caption>
                        The points behind the construction. <m>Q</m> lies on the connecting circle (orange, on diameter <m>AB</m>) and on the auxiliary circle (light red, radius <m>R+r</m>); the tangent is drawn at <m>T_1'</m>.
                    </caption>
                    <image width="80%">
                        <shortdescription>
                            Two circles centred at A and B. A dashed connecting circle on diameter AB and a dashed auxiliary circle of radius R plus r meet at Q, where angle AQB is a right angle. The line QB meets circle B at T-one-prime, where a line is drawn tangent to circle B; this same line is tangent to circle A at T-one and crosses AB at O-prime between the two circles.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{4}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){A}
                            \tkzDefPoint(9,0){B}
                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{T1p}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{h1}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h1--T1p](A) \tkzGetPoint{T1}
                            \tkzInterLL(T1,T1p)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{Op}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawCircle[blue, thick](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[red, thick](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[red!40, dashed](B,c)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[orange, dashed](I,B)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.1 and 0.3](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(A,Q B,Q)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.4 and 0.6, thick](T1,T1p)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[blue](A,T1)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,I,Q,T1p,T1,Op)
                            %% --- MARK ---
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.4](A,Q,B)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](B,T1p,T1)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](T1p,T1,A)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](I){$I$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above](Q){$Q$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](T1p){$T_1'$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T1){$T_1$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](Op){$O'$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above left, pos=0.5](Q,T1p){$r$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above right, pos=0.5](T1p,B){$R$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain why <m>\angle AQB = 90^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Write down the length <m>BQ</m>, and hence show that <m>QT_1' = r</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The tangent line is perpendicular to the radius <m>BT_1'</m>. Explain why this tangent line is <em>parallel</em> to <m>AQ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using parts (b) and (c), show that the perpendicular distance from <m>A</m> to the tangent line is exactly <m>r</m>. Why does this prove that the line is tangent to circle <m>A</m>?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain why <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> lie on <em>opposite</em> sides of the tangent line, so that it is a <em>transverse</em> (and not a direct) common tangent.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The second meeting point <m>Q'</m> of the connecting and auxiliary circles gives the second transverse tangent in exactly the same way. Explain briefly why the two tangents are reflections of each other in the line <m>AB</m>, and hence why they meet at a single point <m>O'</m> on <m>AB</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>Q</m> lies on the connecting circle, which has <m>AB</m> as a diameter. An angle subtended by a diameter at a point on the circle is a right angle (the angle in a semicircle), so <m>\angle AQB = 90^\circ</m>. In particular, <m>AQ \perp QB</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>Q</m> lies on the auxiliary circle, centred at <m>B</m> with radius <m>R + r</m>, so <m>BQ = R + r</m>. The point <m>T_1'</m> lies on circle <m>B</m>, so <m>BT_1' = R</m>, and it lies on segment <m>BQ</m>. Therefore
                            <me>QT_1' = BQ - BT_1' = (R + r) - R = r.</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The tangent line is perpendicular to <m>BT_1'</m>. Since <m>T_1'</m> lies on line <m>QB</m>, the radius <m>BT_1'</m> lies along <m>QB</m>, so the tangent line is perpendicular to <m>QB</m>. From part (a), <m>AQ</m> is also perpendicular to <m>QB</m>. Two lines that are perpendicular to the same line are parallel, so the tangent line is parallel to <m>AQ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The tangent line and <m>AQ</m> are parallel, and both are perpendicular to <m>QB</m>. The perpendicular distance between them is therefore the distance measured along <m>QB</m> from <m>Q</m> to <m>T_1'</m>, which is <m>QT_1' = r</m> by part (b). As <m>A</m> lies on the line <m>AQ</m>, the perpendicular distance from <m>A</m> to the tangent line is exactly <m>r</m>. A straight line whose distance from the centre of a circle equals that circle's radius touches the circle at exactly one point, so the line is tangent to circle <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>). It is of course tangent to circle <m>B</m> by construction, so it is a common tangent.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The point <m>T_1'</m> lies <em>between</em> <m>Q</m> and <m>B</m> on segment <m>QB</m>. Because <m>AQ \perp QB</m> at <m>Q</m>, the centre <m>A</m> is level with <m>Q</m> and so lies on the same side of the tangent as <m>Q</m>; the centre <m>B</m> lies beyond <m>T_1'</m>, on the other side. The two circles are therefore on opposite sides of the line, which is exactly what makes it a <em>transverse</em> common tangent rather than a direct one.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The whole construction is symmetric about the line <m>AB</m>: the points <m>Q</m> and <m>Q'</m> are the two intersections of the connecting and auxiliary circles, and these are mirror images of each other in <m>AB</m>. Reflecting the first tangent in <m>AB</m> therefore produces the second tangent, and two lines that are mirror images in <m>AB</m> must meet on the mirror line itself — so both tangents pass through a single point <m>O'</m> on <m>AB</m>. (Comparing the similar right triangles <m>AT_1O'</m> and <m>BT_1'O'</m> shows further that <m>O'</m> divides <m>AB</m> in the ratio <m>AO' : O'B = r : R</m>, agreeing with the Key Ideas box.)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-transverse-tangent-length-proof">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A transverse common tangent <m>TT'</m> touches circle <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>) at <m>T</m> and circle <m>B</m> (radius <m>R</m>, <m>R \gt r</m>) at <m>T'</m>. The circles are on opposite sides of the tangent. The distance between the centres is <m>d = AB</m>.
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="fig-transverse-exer2-proof-setup">
                    <caption>
                        Transverse common tangent <m>TT'</m> and the auxiliary right triangle <m>ABM</m>,
                        where <m>AM \parallel TT'</m> and <m>M</m> lies on the extension of <m>BT'</m> beyond <m>T'</m>.
                    </caption>
                    <image width="75%">
                        <shortdescription>
                            Two circles at A and B on opposite sides of a tangent line that touches
                            circle A at T and circle B at T-prime. A dashed line from A parallel to
                            TT-prime meets the extension of BT-prime beyond T-prime at M, forming
                            right triangle ABM with the right angle at M.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            %% --- SET ---
                            % Generic diagram: r=2, R=3.5, d=9 (symbolic labels only).
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\r}{2}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\R}{3.5}%
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rt}{\R+\r}%
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 9/0/B}
                            %% --- CALCULATE ---
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\r) \tkzGetPoint{a}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\R) \tkzGetPoint{b}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rt) \tkzGetPoint{c}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                            \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,c) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Q'}
                            \tkzInterLC[near](Q,B)(B,b) \tkzGetFirstPoint{Tp}
                            \tkzDefLine[tangent at=Tp](B) \tkzGetPoint{h}
                            \tkzDefPointBy[projection=onto h--Tp](A) \tkzGetPoint{T}
                            \tkzDefLine[parallel=through A](T,Tp) \tkzGetPoint{aP}
                            \tkzInterLL(A,aP)(B,Tp) \tkzGetPoint{M}
                            %% --- DRAW ---
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](A,a)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](B,b)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed,gray](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[thin](A,T B,M)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[very thick](T,Tp)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](A,M)
                            %% --- MARK ---
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](A,M,B)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.22](Tp,T,A)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.22](T,Tp,B)
                            %% --- LABEL ---
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T,Tp,M)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T){$T$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](Tp){$T'$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](M){$M$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below,font=\small](A,B){$d$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left,font=\small](A,T){$r$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above,sloped,font=\small](T,Tp){$L = TT'$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](B,Tp){$R$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](Tp,M){$r$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            From <m>A</m>, draw a line parallel to <m>TT'</m> meeting the extension of <m>BT'</m> beyond <m>T'</m> at a point <m>M</m>. Explain why <m>BM = R + r</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain why triangle <m>ABM</m> is right-angled at <m>M</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Show that <m>AM = TT'</m>, and hence use Pythagoras' theorem to prove that
                            <md>
                                <mrow>TT' = \sqrt{d^2 - (R + r)^2}.</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>AT \perp TT'</m>, <m>BT' \perp TT'</m>, and <m>AM \parallel TT'</m>, with <m>AT</m> and <m>BT'</m> on opposite sides of <m>TT'</m>, the quadrilateral <m>ATT'M</m> is a rectangle (going around: <m>A</m> to <m>T</m> perpendicular to <m>TT'</m>, then <m>T</m> to <m>T'</m> along the tangent, then <m>T'</m> to <m>M</m> along the extension of <m>BT'</m>, then <m>M</m> back to <m>A</m>). Therefore <m>MT' = AT = r</m>, and so <m>BM = BT' + T'M = R + r</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>AM \parallel TT'</m> and <m>BT'</m> is perpendicular to <m>TT'</m>, the line <m>BM</m> is also perpendicular to <m>AM</m>. Therefore <m>\angle AMB = 90°</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>ATT'M</m> is a rectangle, <m>AM = TT'</m>. Applying Pythagoras to triangle <m>ABM</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> AB^2 \amp= AM^2 + BM^2 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> d^2  \amp= TT'^2 + (R+r)^2 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> TT'  \amp= \sqrt{d^2 - (R+r)^2}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In each part, find the length of the transverse common tangent to the two circles.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 3 cm and 4 cm, centres 25 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 3 cm and 5 cm, centres 17 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 2 cm and 3 cm, centres 13 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 1 cm and 5 cm, centres 10 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p>24 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p>15 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p>12 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p>8 cm</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    In each part we use <m>L = \sqrt{d^2 - (R + r)^2}</m>.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>R + r = 4 + 3 = 7</m> cm, so
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> L \amp= \sqrt{25^2 - 7^2} = \sqrt{625 - 49} = \sqrt{576} = 24 \text{ cm}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>R + r = 5 + 3 = 8</m> cm, so
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> L \amp= \sqrt{17^2 - 8^2} = \sqrt{289 - 64} = \sqrt{225} = 15 \text{ cm}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>R + r = 3 + 2 = 5</m> cm, so
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> L \amp= \sqrt{13^2 - 5^2} = \sqrt{169 - 25} = \sqrt{144} = 12 \text{ cm}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>R + r = 5 + 1 = 6</m> cm, so
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> L \amp= \sqrt{10^2 - 6^2} = \sqrt{100 - 36} = \sqrt{64} = 8 \text{ cm}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In each part, find the distance between the centres of the two circles.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 2 cm and 6 cm, transverse common tangent length 15 cm.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 3 cm and 5 cm, transverse common tangent length 8 cm.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p>17 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>8\sqrt{2}</m> cm</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    In each part we rearrange <m>L^2 = d^2 - (R + r)^2</m> to give <m>d = \sqrt{L^2 + (R + r)^2}</m>.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>R + r = 6 + 2 = 8</m> cm, so
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> d \amp= \sqrt{15^2 + 8^2} = \sqrt{225 + 64} = \sqrt{289} = 17 \text{ cm}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>R + r = 5 + 3 = 8</m> cm, so
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> d \amp= \sqrt{8^2 + 8^2} = \sqrt{64 + 64} = \sqrt{128} = 8\sqrt{2} \text{ cm} \approx 11.3 \text{ cm}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two circles of radii <m>r</m> and <m>R</m> touch each other externally, so that the distance between their centres is <m>d = R + r</m>.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What does the formula <m>L = \sqrt{d^2 - (R+r)^2}</m> give for the length of the transverse common tangent?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What does this result mean geometrically? How many transverse common tangents do two externally touching circles have?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Substituting <m>d = R + r</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>L = \sqrt{(R+r)^2 - (R+r)^2} = \sqrt{0} = 0.</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A length of zero means the two transverse tangents have collapsed to a single point — the point where the two circles touch. Geometrically, when two circles touch externally there is exactly one transverse common tangent, and it passes through the point of contact, perpendicular to the line of centres.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>
</section>
